'''Ueyama No. 2 Kofun''' (上山2号墳) was a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun}} located in {{ill|Heguri, Nara|ja|平群町}}, {{ill|Ikoma District, Nara|ja|生駒郡}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県}}. The tumulus, shaped as a {{ill|Hōfun|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun}}, no longer exists.

== Overview ==
The kofun was situated on the southern slope of the highest point of the Hazukayama Hill in western Nara Prefecture, near the west bank of the {{ill|Tatsutagawa River|ja|竜田川}}, just south of Hikari-ga-oka residential area. Nearby, the northeastern hilltop housed Ueyama No. 1 Kofun (a {{ill|Zenpō-kōen-fun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun}}), while the southern base featured the Nishinomiya Nos. 1 and 2 Kofun (including {{ill|Nishinomiya Kofun|ja|西宮古墳}}). The site was discovered during residential development in 1989–1990, leading to its excavation and subsequent destruction.

The tumulus measured 10 m on its southern side, 7 m on its northern side, and had a depth of 9 m. A U-shaped surrounding ditch, measuring 1.0–1.5 m wide and 0.5 m deep, was identified along the east, north, and west sides. {{Sfn|Murasoro Hitoshi|1990}} The burial structure consisted of a {{ill|Cave Tomb-shiki sekaku|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber}}, opening to the south-southeast. The structure was heavily damaged due to its reuse as a medieval cremation grave, with only fragments of {{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery}} unearthed. The kofun is dated to the mid-{{ill|7th century|ja|7世紀}}, in the terminal period of kofun construction. {{Sfn|Murasoro Hitoshi|1990}} Among the Hazukayama Hill tombs, this is the only one in the Heguri Valley with a yokoguchi-style stone chamber, making it particularly notable.

Today, the stone chamber is preserved in a relocated and restored state on the campus of {{ill|Hanazono University|ja|花園大学}} in Kyoto.

== burial Structure ==
[[File:Ueyama Kofun Group-2, 3D-P.jpg|thumb|300px|right|{{center|Restored Stone Chamber Perspective View}}]]
[[File:Ueyama Kofun Group-2, 3D-N.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Restored Stone Chamber Diagram}}]]
The burial structure featured a {{ill|Cave Tomb-shiki sekaku|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber}}, oriented to the south-southeast. The area are as follows: {{Sfn|Murasoro Hitoshi|1990}}
* Chamber: Approximately 2 m long, 1 m wide, 0.7 m high
* Passageway: 3 m long, 1 m wide

Due to its reuse as a medieval cremation grave, much of the chamber was destroyed, particularly the passageway. The chamber stones, made of granite, were flatly cut and fitted together. A 0.2 m thick stone slab covered the floor. Iron nails, some possibly from the original wooden coffin, were found in the disturbed medieval burial layer, alongside fragments of Sue pottery bowls recovered from the passage and forecourt. {{Sfn|Murasoro Hitoshi|1990}}
<gallery>
Ueyama Kofun Group-2, 3D-B.jpg|Overhead view of restored stone chamber
</gallery>

== Related Facilities ==
* {{ill|Hanazono University|ja|花園大学}} (Nishinokyo Tsubonouchi-chō, Kyoto): The restored stone chamber of Ueyama No. 2 Kofun is preserved in the campus courtyard.

